WEBVTT

p01
00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:04.455
Two Settings areas face the customer directly, and this lesson reads both.

p02
00:00:04.907 --> 00:00:08.768
In the left rail, open Customer Portal, then Portal Overview.

p03
00:00:09.272 --> 00:00:13.935
This hub is the portal your client's members log into, summarized on one screen:

p04
00:00:14.380 --> 00:00:17.638
its status, its address, and a version stamp.

p05
00:00:17.965 --> 00:00:19.726
It's live. Treat it that way.

p06
00:00:20.160 --> 00:00:21.606
Read the tile band.

p07
00:00:22.096 --> 00:00:23.192
Registered members, logins today, average session, uptime, and the share on mobile.

p08
00:00:23.395 --> 00:00:24.490
When someone reports the portal is slow or quiet, this row is your first read.

p09
00:00:24.717 --> 00:00:36.131
Healthy numbers here move the problem somewhere else.

p10
00:00:36.560 --> 00:00:39.667
Four cards sit below, one per configuration area.

p11
00:00:40.015 --> 00:00:40.635
Branding, features, access, and content.

p12
00:00:40.844 --> 00:00:41.422
Each card previews its own headline values,

p13
00:00:41.638 --> 00:00:43.072
like the login method and whether one time passwords are required.

p14
00:00:43.931 --> 00:00:53.920
You can answer most portal questions from these cards without opening anything.

p15
00:00:54.320 --> 00:00:56.192
Below the cards, two panels.

p16
00:00:56.574 --> 00:01:01.304
Recent activity lists what members did in the last day, including a security line:

p17
00:01:01.642 --> 00:01:04.053
three failed login attempts from one address.

p18
00:01:04.506 --> 00:01:09.738
Portal Health confirms the A-P-I connection, the certificate,

p19
00:01:09.995 --> 00:01:11.501
and when the portal was last published.

p20
00:01:11.752 --> 00:01:15.283
And note the button top right.

p21
00:01:15.535 --> 00:01:17.158
Publish Changes pushes edits live to real customers. Support never clicks it.

p22
00:01:17.600 --> 00:01:19.418
Open Branding and Appearance.

p23
00:01:19.939 --> 00:01:20.824
Three tabs.

p24
00:01:21.554 --> 00:01:28.040
Visual Identity holds the portal's name, tagline, logo, and header style,

p25
00:01:28.779 --> 00:01:32.171
with a live preview underneath.

p26
00:01:32.718 --> 00:01:34.759
Everything a customer sees before signing in gets styled here.

p27
00:01:35.156 --> 00:01:36.960
There's a Save and Publish button at the bottom. We read; we never save.

p28
00:01:37.360 --> 00:01:39.477
Next, Features and Modules.

p29
00:01:40.169 --> 00:01:42.628
Every portal capability is a section here,

p30
00:01:42.832 --> 00:01:48.125
from membership plans to gift cards to vehicle management, each with its own sub options.

p31
00:01:48.544 --> 00:01:54.409
One catch: this page says nine of ten modules enabled, while the hub card said seven of nine.

p32
00:01:54.795 --> 00:01:55.901
The two disagree.

p33
00:01:56.126 --> 00:01:59.920
When you need the real number, read it here, and flag the mismatch.

p34
00:02:00.397 --> 00:02:03.651
Open Access and Security, the page for login trouble.

p35
00:02:04.500 --> 00:02:07.574
The Authentication tab shows how members can sign in:

p36
00:02:08.022 --> 00:02:13.034
phone yes, email yes, membership number no, and no guest access.

p37
00:02:13.659 --> 00:02:17.488
Below that, the one time password rules and the password policy.

p38
00:02:17.800 --> 00:02:21.742
A customer locked out of the portal? Start on this page, every time.

p39
00:02:22.160 --> 00:02:24.021
Then Content and Messaging.

p40
00:02:24.559 --> 00:02:25.766
Welcome text, footer, contact details, and the FAQ list.

p41
00:02:26.065 --> 00:02:26.447
Plain language a confused customer reads first.

p42
00:02:26.736 --> 00:02:37.120
If a member quotes the portal saying something odd, this is where that wording lives.

p43
00:02:37.598 --> 00:02:38.663
That's the portal.

p44
00:02:39.319 --> 00:02:45.901
For a login complaint, check two settings, the login method and whether O-T-P is required,

p45
00:02:46.285 --> 00:02:49.161
then look for failed attempts in the activity feed.

p46
00:02:50.480 --> 00:02:56.242
Back to Portal Overview, and remember the rule: nothing gets published, nothing gets saved.

p47
00:02:56.780 --> 00:02:57.477
Part two. In the left rail, open A-I Agent, then Overview.

p48
00:02:57.874 --> 00:03:01.906
This is the automated agent answering your client's customers on web chat, text, and phone.

p49
00:03:02.319 --> 00:03:07.732
The header says it's live on three channels.

p50
00:03:08.202 --> 00:03:14.216
Same posture as the portal: everything here is read only.

p51
00:03:14.640 --> 00:03:16.012
Read the metric band.

p52
00:03:16.841 --> 00:03:18.301
Conversations this month, average handle time, a satisfaction score.

p53
00:03:18.562 --> 00:03:21.172
The number to watch is containment rate,

p54
00:03:21.959 --> 00:03:29.291
the share of conversations the agent finished without a person.

p55
00:03:29.612 --> 00:03:32.374
Seventy eight percent here. When that slides, humans are picking up the slack.

p56
00:03:32.876 --> 00:03:34.099
Three channel cards.

p57
00:03:34.934 --> 00:03:38.097
Web chat carries the most volume and contains the most.

p58
00:03:38.632 --> 00:03:41.688
Text runs through a provisioned number with quiet hours on.

p59
00:03:42.341 --> 00:03:44.481
Voice is newer, still marked beta, with recording consent enabled.

p60
00:03:44.781 --> 00:03:51.580
Each card shows its own contained percentage, so you can spot which channel is struggling.

p61
00:03:52.135 --> 00:03:53.461
Now the capabilities panel.

p62
00:03:53.461 --> 00:03:57.082
Six actions the agent can take on its own,

p63
00:03:57.082 --> 00:04:02.587
from looking up an account to processing a small refund to escalating to a human.

p64
00:04:02.587 --> 00:04:04.576
They run through secure platform A-P-Is,

p65
00:04:04.576 --> 00:04:07.891
and each one can be switched off individually under Configuration.

p66
00:04:08.320 --> 00:04:09.090
Open Configuration.

p67
00:04:09.090 --> 00:04:13.610
Status tiles up top, including a refund cap of fifty dollars,

p68
00:04:13.610 --> 00:04:17.844
then five tabs covering identity, channels, tools, safety, and the model.

p69
00:04:17.844 --> 00:04:23.295
One caution: in the captured tenant this page renders as an unsaved form

p70
00:04:23.295 --> 00:04:25.220
for a different demo brand.

p71
00:04:25.220 --> 00:04:30.193
Read the structure, trust nothing as the live values, and never save.

p72
00:04:30.720 --> 00:04:31.781
Next, Knowledge Base.

p73
00:04:31.781 --> 00:04:35.840
These are the documents the agent searches before it answers,

p74
00:04:35.840 --> 00:04:38.316
so it quotes policy instead of guessing.

p75
00:04:38.316 --> 00:04:41.991
Tiles track articles, indexing, and the last sync.

p76
00:04:41.991 --> 00:04:48.510
In this capture the table sits empty, which is a tenant quirk, not the real agent.

p77
00:04:48.960 --> 00:04:50.647
Open Channels and Deployment, and keep your hands off the buttons.

p78
00:04:50.977 --> 00:04:53.156
Each channel block carries a test control:

p79
00:04:54.468 --> 00:04:56.683
send a test message, send a test text, place a test call.

p80
00:04:57.014 --> 00:04:58.286
All three reach a real channel.

p81
00:04:58.592 --> 00:04:59.861
None of them get clicked, ever, in the demo tenant.

p82
00:05:00.204 --> 00:05:09.900
Read the uptime and latency, and move on.

p83
00:05:10.389 --> 00:05:11.770
Then Conversations.

p84
00:05:12.101 --> 00:05:13.074
The transcript log: who talked to the agent, on which channel, about what, and how it ended.

p85
00:05:13.464 --> 00:05:17.485
This is your audit trail when a client asks what the agent actually said.

p86
00:05:17.949 --> 00:05:25.600
Empty in this capture, and the Export control stays untouched.

p87
00:05:26.059 --> 00:05:27.975
Escalations is the page to remember.

p88
00:05:27.975 --> 00:05:33.078
When the agent hits a limit, a refund over the cap, an angry customer,

p89
00:05:33.078 --> 00:05:38.275
a direct ask for a manager, or a stalled conversation, it hands off here.

p90
00:05:38.275 --> 00:05:42.301
Each row shows the reason, the priority, and who claimed it.

p91
00:05:42.301 --> 00:05:45.814
Don't click Claim Next; that assigns a live escalation to you.

p92
00:05:46.240 --> 00:05:47.789
Last, Analytics.

p93
00:05:48.364 --> 00:05:53.757
The monthly review view: volume, containment, escalation rate, satisfaction,

p94
00:05:54.080 --> 00:05:57.713
and what the agent costs to run, per channel and per conversation.

p95
00:05:58.537 --> 00:06:02.588
When a client asks whether the agent is worth it, this page is the answer.

p96
00:06:03.109 --> 00:06:04.794
Export stays alone here too.

p97
00:06:05.262 --> 00:06:06.718
Two areas, one habit.

p98
00:06:06.718 --> 00:06:12.135
The portal hub answers login complaints through the login method and O-T-P settings,

p99
00:06:12.135 --> 00:06:16.138
and the agent hands humans a conversation through the Escalations queue,

p100
00:06:16.138 --> 00:06:18.971
which mirrors into the C-R-M Agent Console.

p101
00:06:18.971 --> 00:06:21.439
You read everything and published nothing.

p102
00:06:21.439 --> 00:06:23.600
Close Settings, and you're done.

